\begin_layout Standard
On one hand, status goods are those that indicate consumer's exclusivity
 but on the other, they are goods that create bandwagon effects for those
 who don't have much status.
 For both the modeler and the empirical analyst, the issue that status goods
 imply higher status both for those who already have higher status and those
 who don't is addressed with its association with a reference group .
 The consumers often do not know the reason to purchase status items as
 they would for purchasing food or clothing items.
 The association with a reference group also addresses the descriptive significa
nce of the conscpiuous consumption - argument without which the mechanisms
 of individious comparison (IC) and pecuniary emulation (PE) identified
 by Veblen would remain normative concerns.
 The uncertainty towards each other's status - i.e.
 the lack of a clear reason for purchasing status item - could in fact be
 said to drive conspicuous consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the view articulated by Cole-Maliath as non-transactional choices
 excercised by the consumer.
 We buld upon the framework where consumer participate in competitions with
 status items (see Frank) in an environment of income and wealth differences.
 The specific goal of in the proposed chapter is to explain how income differenc
es could influence status consumption choices for the consumer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an approach similar to Cole and Maliath, we argue that the consumer does
 not get utility from the references and allow the uncertainty arising out
 of non-transactional choices to contribute to the consumer's future expectation
s for status competitions.
 The core of the argument that is that if status goods - such as jewelry
 or club membership - offered returns contributing to status that are in
 no way more uncertain than the purchase of expensive long-term assets such
 as a house, the representative consumer would know of the futility of status
 consumption relative to saving towards higher wealth.
 Status consumption thus cannot be understood in the intertemporal framework
 without arguing that visible or conspicuous good offer a utility different
 from the one that is derived from regular goods.
 While the split of utility into visible and non-visible terms allows us
 to understand status consumption in a setting where signaling goods are
 accessible to everyone, the empirical distinctions between regular and
 visible items could be more difficult in environments of extreme income
 and wealth differences (e.g.
 in developing economies where relative wealth would be more easily visible).
 This motivates the proposed approach to viewing status consumption as a
 risky position in an intertemporal framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The view of status as wealth under uncertainty clears up that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

having status
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cannot be a prerequisite for participating in status competitions.
 If only those with status needed to spend on status goods, we would see
 no status consumption in societies as they moved towards equality.
 Instead, as the empirical literature from Hirsch, Galbraith notes, the
 improvement in median incomes seems to have increased the focus on status
 items in the developed world.
 The rise in status consumption with falling inequality in the economy is
 in agreement with the view of status under uncertainty since with less
 income differences in an economy, status goods are all what consumers can
 use to participate in competitions for status.
 In other words, when basic amenities are guaranteed (i.e.
 certain) for everyone and wealth differences are lower, the avenues for
 demonstrating status are limited to conspicuous items.
\end_layout

