\begin_layout Standard
In contrast with the conventional intertemporal approach where a substitution
 between consuming now vs gaining interest through assets is considered,
 the imprecise value towards status allows us to talk about the evaluation
 of future risk through status consumption.
 The underlying assumption is that the transition probability changes with
 status consumption and encompasses all possible paths in which a consumer
 could to rise in the hierarchy of income or and wealth.
 With that view of the transtion probabilty, we consider a utility derived
 through absolute value of assets as well as the non-transactional state
 of being a particular asset-band.
 This is similar to the Cole-Malaith approach where consumers would care
 about about status because in equilibrium it affects variables that enter
 the utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[ABA assumption] There are two key assumptions that characterise this model.
 The first assumption is that transition probability faced by all consumers
 within the reference are the same.
 The differentiation in asset-bands represents the environment of income
 and asset differences that influence varied status goals.
 [ bags, private jets, food all represent different clases ] We view such
