\begin_layout Standard
[INTERCHANGEABILITY Reference] The second assumption is that comparisons
 of status involve status consumption only within a particular asset-band.
 In other words, the asset-band identities dominate status comparisons across
 different asset-bands so that no two consumers in the two different asset-bands
 are in same status competition.
 This makes empirical sense for two reasons - first the status comparisons
 require a certain notion of interchangeability
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is also implicit in the status inference approaches - which assume
 that all consumers have the same inference function.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Second, while status goals could offer some utility in lieu of higher assets
 - they are not more important in the long term than extreme differences
 in wealth.
 Consider for example, a classical musician who considers herself of higher
 status than the country musician even though she has a lower accumulated
 wealth than the country musician.
 There are two possibilities when this might happen in the model.
 First is when the two musicians belong to the same asset-band and the second
 when they don't.
 When the classical musician considers herself in the same reference group
 as that of the country musician, her private held belief of a higher status
 relies on certain qualities of classical music that carry more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

value
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (at least privately) than the crowds that country music can draw.
 This private view is however unknown to consumers both in other asset bands
 and within her own.
 There is no reason to think that consumers having a higher preference for
 classical musicians would result in a better income for country musicians.
 Any non-private notion of status in other words must be reflected in wealth
 differences among the musicians.
  The country musicians having higher wealth would have higher status in
 the band - except for the qualities of sublimity (and a history of elite
 patronage) that might enable an immense future material growth (however
 unlikely) for the classical musician.
 Thus if both classical and country musicians are in the same asset-band,
 they compare themselves both on the net worth they achieve through labour
 and how prepared they are to be in the next/higher asset-band e.g.
 with the proper education (theoretical foundations) or the sophistication
 to build future social networks.
 The two types of musicians being in the same asset-band exposes their decision-
making to same uncertainty and probability of future success as they rank
 themselves in status.
 Whether they are in the same asset-band or not in the model depends on
 the whether most classical musicians and most country musicians make comparable
 income or not.
 When the classical musician and the country musician do not consider themselves
 in the same reference group, they must carry different asset-values (overall)
 and face different probability of future asset growths.
 This is likely when the payoffs from classical music and country music
 gigs are so different that the classical musicians and country musicians
 can never be in the same asset-band.
 The assumption that asset-bands dominate status comparison only asserts
 that status comparisons require a notion of interchangeability that does
 not overcome extreme wealth differences.
